  <li><a href="https://www.adobe.com/it/products/photoshop-lightroom-classic.html" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Adobe Lightroom Classic</a>, alas, the best photo editing software out there. I hate Adobe, but it works so damn good. I‚Äôm doing my best to completely switch to the two following programs but, damn, it‚Äôs so hard. Also: I have to keep Lightroom on my device because it‚Äôs impossible to move photography edits commited with Lightroom to Darktable.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.darktable.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Darktable</a>, widely used (still, not the first option for pros) photo editing software. I wish I‚Äôd love it but, damn, it‚Äôs so friggin complicated.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.digikam.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Digikam</a>, a photo management software.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.android.com/filetransfer/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Android File Transfer</a>, the name says it all. It‚Äôs simple and it works great.</li>
  <li><a href="https://freemacsoft.net/appcleaner/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">AppCleaner</a> it‚Äôs not Open Source, but, damn, it‚Äôs so useful I have to keep it. As an Open Source alternative, I‚Äôm trying to figure out how <a href="http://onnati.net/apptrap/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">AppTrap</a> works.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.audacityteam.org/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Audacity</a>, audio editing software. I know, I have Garage Band which is awesome but‚Ä¶ Audacity works the same way anywhere.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.backtrack.team/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Backtrack</a>, the Holy Graal for university students which get easily distracted (me). It allows you to recover audio up to 5 hours before. It‚Äôs not Open Source and I payed 2‚Ç¨ for it. Totally worth it.</li>
  <li><a href="https://www.balena.io/etcher/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">balenaEtcher</a>, the safest, simplest and quickest software to flash OS images to external drives.</li>
